# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: histidine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:histidine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:histidine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase uses oxygen to cleave the aromatic ring of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, giving 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde.
[src:histidine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The kynurenine pathway of tryptophan catabolism leads to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide and supplies the nicotinic acid component of that cofactor.
[src:histidine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] Alternatively, 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde can be acted on by the enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase to give 2-aminomuconic semialdehyde, an unstable open-chain precursor of picolinic acid.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] 2-Aminomuconic acid is a six-carbon molecule bearing two carboxyl groups, two conjugated double bonds, and a primary amino substituent at carbon 2.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The molecule is commonly encountered in its ionized form, 2-aminomuconate, under physiological and environmental aqueous conditions.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Specific physical constants such as pKa values, solubility, and spectroscopic data are not comprehensively tabulated in the primary literature and should be added only with a verified source.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In microbial biodegradation of aromatic xenobiotics, for example certain nitroaromatic compounds, where ring-cleavage pathways produce aminomuconic intermediates prior to further downstream processing.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The compound appears as a catabolic intermediate in several bacterial strains studied under laboratory conditions.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In the oxidative degradation of tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway, intermediates with structural relation to aminomuconate are formed during enzymatic ring opening and aldehyde oxidation steps.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Wherever it appears, the ionized form 2-aminomuconate is typically the biologically relevant species.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Details such as kinetic constants, mechanism and gene names vary by organism and strain and should be cited from the primary enzymology literature for each specific claim.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In environmental microbiology, pathways involving 2-aminomuconate are part of bacterial systems that allow mineralization of aromatic pollutants, converting recalcitrant compounds into metabolites that join central carbon metabolism.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Such pathways are of interest for biodegradation and bioremediation research.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde is an intermediate in the kynurenine pathway of tryptophan metabolism, which leads to picolinic acid or quinolinic acid.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase produces it from 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde, a compound which would form quinolinic acid in the absence of that enzyme.
[src:histidine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde itself is chemically unstable and spontaneously ring-closes to picolinic acid, with loss of water.
[src:histidine/3-methylhistidine] 3-Methylhistidine is a metabolic product that is produced in the body via the enzymatic methylation of histidine during peptide bond synthesis and the methylation of actin and myosin.
[src:histidine/3-methylhistidine] The normal concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the urine of healthy adult humans has been detected and quantified in a range of 3.63–69.27 micromoles per millimole (μmol/mmol) of creatinine, with most studies reporting the average urinary concentration between 15 and 20 μmol/mmol of creatinine.
[src:histidine/3-methylhistidine] The average concentration of 3-methylhistidine in human blood plasma has been detected and quantified at 2.85 micromolar (μM) with a range of 0.0–5.9 μM.
[src:histidine/3-methylhistidine] The average concentration of 3-methylhistidine in human cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) has been detected and quantified at 3.82 μM with a range of 1.39–6.25 μM.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:histidine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:histidine/4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic-acid] It is an intermediary compound in the biosynthesis of scytonemin.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine was first isolated by Albrecht Kossel and Sven Gustaf Hedin in 1896.
[src:histidine/histidine] The name stems from its discovery in tissue, from ἱστός *histós* "tissue".
[src:histidine/histidine] It is also a precursor to histamine, a vital inflammatory agent in immune responses.
[src:histidine/histidine] At neutral or physiological pH, the imidazole side chain is neutral.
[src:histidine/histidine] The imidazole side chain in histidine has a p*K*a of approximately 6.0.
[src:histidine/histidine] Thus, below a pH of 6, the imidazole ring is mostly protonated and carries a positive +1 charge (as described by the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation).
[src:histidine/histidine] The resulting imidazolium ring bears two NH bonds and has a positive charge.
[src:histidine/histidine] The positive charge is equally distributed between both nitrogen atoms and can be represented with two equally important resonance structures.
[src:histidine/histidine] Sometimes, the symbol **Hip** is used for this protonated form instead of the usual His.
[src:histidine/histidine] Above pH 6, one of the two protons is lost.
[src:histidine/histidine] The remaining proton of the imidazole ring can reside on either nitrogen atom, giving rise to what are known as the N3-H or N1-H tautomers.
[src:histidine/histidine] In the N1-H tautomer, the NH group is nearer the backbone.
[src:histidine/histidine] These neutral tautomers, also referred to as Nε (or Nτ, tau meaning *tele* — far) and Nδ (or Nπ, pi meaning *pros* — near), are sometimes referred to with symbols **Hie** and **Hid**, respectively.
[src:histidine/histidine] The imidazole/imidazolium ring of histidine is aromatic at all pH values.
[src:histidine/histidine] Under certain conditions, all three ion-forming groups of histidine can be charged forming the histidinium cation.
[src:histidine/histidine] The acid-base properties of the imidazole side chain are relevant to the catalytic mechanism of many enzymes.
[src:histidine/histidine] In catalytic triads, the basic nitrogen of histidine abstracts a proton from serine, threonine, or cysteine to activate it as a nucleophile.
[src:histidine/histidine] In a histidine proton shuttle, histidine is used to quickly shuttle protons.
[src:histidine/histidine] It can do this by abstracting a proton with its basic nitrogen to make a positively charged intermediate and then use another molecule, a buffer, to extract the proton from its acidic nitrogen.
[src:histidine/histidine] In carbonic anhydrases, a histidine proton shuttle is utilized to rapidly shuttle protons away from a zinc-bound water molecule to quickly regenerate the active form of the enzyme.
[src:histidine/histidine] In helices E and F of hemoglobin, histidine influences binding of dioxygen as well as carbon monoxide.
[src:histidine/histidine] This interaction enhances the affinity of Fe(II) for O2 but destabilizes the binding of CO, which binds only 200 times stronger in hemoglobin, compared to 20,000 times stronger in free heme.
[src:histidine/histidine] The tautomerism and acid-base properties of the imidazole side chain has been characterized by 15N NMR spectroscopy.
[src:histidine/histidine] The two 15N chemical shifts are similar (about 200 ppm, relative to nitric acid on the sigma scale, on which increased shielding corresponds to increased chemical shift).
[src:histidine/histidine] NMR spectral measurements shows that the chemical shift of N1-H drops slightly, whereas the chemical shift of N3-H drops considerably (about 190 vs.
[src:histidine/histidine] This change indicates that the N1-H tautomer is preferred, possibly due to hydrogen bonding to the neighboring ammonium.
[src:histidine/histidine] The shielding at N3 is substantially reduced due to the second-order paramagnetic effect, which involves a symmetry-allowed interaction between the nitrogen lone pair and the excited π* states of the aromatic ring.
[src:histidine/histidine] At pH > 9, the chemical shifts of N1 and N3 are approximately 185 and 170 ppm.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine forms complexes with many metal ions.
[src:histidine/histidine] The imidazole sidechain of the histidine residue commonly serves as a ligand in metalloproteins.
[src:histidine/histidine] One example is the axial base attached to Fe in myoglobin and hemoglobin.
[src:histidine/histidine] Poly-histidine tags (of six or more consecutive H residues) are utilized for protein purification by binding to columns with nickel or cobalt, with micromolar affinity.
[src:histidine/histidine] Natural poly-histidine peptides, found in the venom of the viper *Atheris squamigera* have been shown to bind Zn(II), Ni(II) and Cu(II) and affect the function of venom metalloproteases.
[src:histidine/histidine] N-terminal histidines are known to function as bidentate ligands, with a metal (generally copper) bound to both the amine of the N-terminus and the Nδ of the histidine; the Nε is often methylated.
[src:histidine/histidine] Although recently discovered, this "histidine brace" motif is critical in biogeochemical cycles: it functions as the active site of lytic polysaccharide monooxygenases (LPMOs), which break down unreactive polysaccharides such as cellulose.
[src:histidine/histidine] It is proposed that the evolution of these enzymes in fungi corresponds to the first widespread ability to decompose woody plant mass, leading to the end of the Carboniferous era and its mass accumulation of coal deposits.
[src:histidine/histidine] l-Histidine is an essential amino acid that is not synthesized *de novo* in humans.
[src:histidine/histidine] Humans and other animals must ingest histidine or histidine-containing proteins.
[src:histidine/histidine] The biosynthesis of histidine has been widely studied in prokaryotes such as *E. coli*.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine synthesis in *E. coli* involves eight gene products (His1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, and 8) and it occurs in ten steps.
[src:histidine/histidine] This is possible because a single gene product has the ability to catalyze more than one reaction.
[src:histidine/histidine] For example, as shown in the pathway, His4 catalyzes four different steps in the pathway.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine is synthesized from phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP), which is made from ribose-5-phosphate by ribose-phosphate diphosphokinase in the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:histidine/histidine] The first reaction of histidine biosynthesis is the condensation of PRPP and adenosine triphosphate (ATP) by the enzyme ATP-phosphoribosyl transferase.
[src:histidine/histidine] ATP-phosphoribosyl transferase is indicated by His1 in the image.
[src:histidine/histidine] His4 gene product then hydrolyzes the product of the condensation, phosphoribosyl-ATP, producing phosphoribosyl-AMP (PRAMP), which is an irreversible step.
[src:histidine/histidine] His4 then catalyzes the formation of phosphoribosylformiminoAICAR-phosphate, which is then converted to phosphoribulosylformimino-AICAR-P by the His6 gene product.
[src:histidine/histidine] His7 splits phosphoribulosylformimino-AICAR-P to form d-erythro-imidazole-glycerol-phosphate.
[src:histidine/histidine] After, His3 forms imidazole acetol-phosphate releasing water.
[src:histidine/histidine] His5 then makes l-histidinol-phosphate, which is then hydrolyzed by His2 making histidinol.
[src:histidine/histidine] His4 catalyzes the oxidation of l-histidinol to form l-histidinal, an amino aldehyde.
[src:histidine/histidine] In the last step, l-histidinal is converted to l-histidine.
[src:histidine/histidine] The histidine biosynthesis pathway has been studied in the fungus *Neurospora crassa*, and a gene (*His-3*) encoding a multienzyme complex was found that was similar to the *His4* gene of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:histidine/histidine] A genetic study of *N. crassa* histidine mutants indicated that the individual activities of the multienzyme complex occur in discrete, contiguous sections of the *His-3* genetic map, suggesting that the different activities of the multienzyme complex are encoded separately from each other.
[src:histidine/histidine] However, mutants were also found that lacked all three activities simultaneously, suggesting that some mutations cause loss of function of the complex as a whole.
[src:histidine/histidine] Like animals and microorganisms, plants need histidine for their growth and development.
[src:histidine/histidine] But unlike animals, microorganisms and plants can synthesize histidine.
[src:histidine/histidine] Both synthesize histidine from the biochemical intermediate phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate.
[src:histidine/histidine] In general, the histidine biosynthesis is very similar in plants and microorganisms.
[src:histidine/histidine] This pathway requires energy in order to occur; therefore, the presence of ATP activates the first enzyme of the pathway, ATP-phosphoribosyl transferase (shown as His1 in the image on the right).
[src:histidine/histidine] ATP-phosphoribosyl transferase is the rate determining enzyme, which is regulated through feedback inhibition, meaning that it is inhibited in the presence of the product, histidine.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine can be metabolized into glutamate, which is readily metabolized into AKG (alpha-ketoglutarate), making histidine one of the amino acids whose metabolites can become citric acid cycle intermediates.
[src:histidine/histidine] In prokaryotes, histidine first undergoes deamination, the removal of its amino group by the emzyme histidase.
[src:histidine/histidine] This step produces ammonia and urocanic acid (urocanate).
[src:histidine/histidine] The enzyme urocanase then converts urocanic acid into imidazolonepropionate (4-imidazolone-5-propionate).
[src:histidine/histidine] The enzyme imidazolonepropionase then converts imidazolonepropionate into formiminoglutamate (FIGLU).
[src:histidine/histidine] The enzyme formimidoyltransferase cyclodeaminase removes the formimino group (which is transferred to tetrahydrofolate), leaving behind a glutamate molecule.
[src:histidine/histidine] Glutamate can then be deaminated by glutamate dehydrogenase or transaminated to form α-ketoglutarate.
[src:histidine/histidine] The Food and Nutrition Board (FNB) of the U.S.
[src:histidine/histidine] Institute of Medicine set Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for essential amino acids in 2002.
[src:histidine/histidine] For histidine, for adults 19 years and older, 14 mg/kg body weight/day.
[src:histidine/histidine] Supplemental histidine is being investigated for use in a variety of different conditions, including neurological disorders, atopic dermatitis, metabolic syndrome, diabetes, uraemic anaemia, ulcers, inflammatory bowel diseases, malignancies, and muscle performance during strenuous exercise.
[src:histidine/histidine] Histidine’s role in skin health has attracted research interest because the amino acid is a precursor to filaggrin, a structural protein that helps maintain the integrity of the skin’s outer barrier.
[src:histidine/histidine] Filaggrin is rich in histidine and, when broken down, contributes to the natural moisturizing factor that helps retain moisture and supports barrier function.
